    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-2782715">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-2782715">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,2782715)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-2782715">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/ajmansfield" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2238949); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2238949&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610227276" alt="AJMansfield" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2238949)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/ajmansfield" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2238949); return false;" >AJMansfield</a></span> <span class="odate time_1491233248 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">03 Apr 2017 15:27</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2782715">
									

<p>That is not what this explanation is. Only a single thread can ever be observed at any one time, in order to observe a new thread one has to shift to that thread, which is irreversible, and in fact it makes more sense to treat alternate threads as rather purely theoretical concepts than as 'real' alternate universes.</p>
<p>Quantum mechanics actually contains a similar concept when you get deep enough in, with the idea that a quantum-random event actually creates a set of parallel universes, which then interact with each other to give the observed outputs. We don't really consider these alternate universes to be 'real' in any sense, merely a convenient explanation.</p>
<p>Philosophers and religious types might want to debate you on the morals of time travel. On one side they might argue you are abandoning the people of the thread to their fate. On the other, though, since we can't observe a thread after leaving it, you could argue that these universes are destroyed along with everyone in them when we leave. Still a third camp could argue that we are just legitimately modifying the past of just this one universe, but disagree about the ethics of 'not accepting fate' or some such BS.</p>
<p>None of these arguments get anyone anywhere though, as fundamentally there is no way to be sure - all we know is that certain things are more likely than others to happen in our own universe, and this alternative world line model happens to give answers that match what we observe experimentally.</p>
<p>Also (out of universe) note that not every story uses the same time travel mechanics; in particular this theory does not allow for the 'ripple effect' as seen in Back To The Future, nor some of the &quot;wibbly-wobbly, timey-wimey&#8230; stuff&quot; that goes on in Doctor Who. This is not meant to be an all-encompassing only-correct-way-to-time-travel, but merely one system, albeit one with rigorous theoretical foundations. If some story doesn't work right with it, then by all means reject it and use your own time travel.</p>

							</div>

								
