						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,2782791)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-2782791">
																		time travel threads.
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/aceofmoxes" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2943332); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2943332&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610227276" alt="Aceofmoxes" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2943332)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/aceofmoxes" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2943332); return false;" >Aceofmoxes</a></span> <span class="odate time_1491238767 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">03 Apr 2017 16:59</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2782791">
									

<p>Perhaps I misunderstood, then.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Once an object leaves a given thread, it is im­pos­si­ble for that ob­ject to ever re­turn to that ex­act same thread.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This line suggests the 'origin' thread continues to exist. Later, you suggest the 'destination' thread is created by &quot;bi­fur­ca­tion.&quot; There's nothing in the article that says other threads are purely theoretical.</p>
<p>The quantum mechanics thing isn't similar. That's a thought exercise to find the solution.</p>
<p>I don't see the moral argument here, but</p>
<blockquote>
<p>it makes more sense to treat alternate threads as rather purely theoretical concepts than as 'real' alternate universes.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>would make a huge difference.</p>
<p>For a introductory textbook, it feels ill-thought out. You should put more of the above statement into it. Also, more examples would flesh it out. Your chapter 2 is better.</p>

							</div>

								
					
