																		Numbers and pedantry!
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/wu-wei" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(433760); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=433760&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610227276" alt="Wu Wei" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=433760)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/wu-wei" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(433760); return false;" >Wu Wei</a></span> <span class="odate time_1492108800 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">13 Apr 2017 18:40</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2791339">
									

<p>I like the style of this; it really does seem like the beginning of an introductory textbook. One note about the numbers, since I did some crunching (and thought maybe too hard about this):</p>
<ol>
<li>I believe that the answer to Exercise 1.3.2 is <span class="math-inline">$2 \times 10^{19}$</span> kg, which is <a href="http://www.wolframalpha.com/input/?i=68.3+femtokilogram+second^3+%2F+%2815+picosecond%29^3+in+kilograms">about the size of a large asteroid or small dwarf planet</a>. Unless the Earth itself was used as a ballast, to be able to construct something like this that could fit in a terrestrial building or complex would require some changes to the parameters (e.g. <a href="http://www.wolframalpha.com/input/?i=1.e-3+femtokilogram+second^3+%2F+%2810+nanosecond%29^3+in+kilograms">a &quot;draw&quot; of one attoxyank with a ballast moving 10 nanoseconds</a>, implying either a lower-than-modern clock speed or the need to &quot;alternate&quot; between N ballasts, each of which is used every N cycles).</li>
<li>This integrated circuit also requires power use of <a href="http://www.wolframalpha.com/input/?i=68.3+femtokilogram+second^3+*+%281.e20+Joule%2Fkilogram%2Fsecond^3%29+%2F+15+ns+in+watts">around 0.4553 PW</a>, which means you wouldn't be able to run it for long (barring an anomalous power source).</li>
<li>However, 68.3 femtoxyanks would be way more than one would probably need anyway for things like branch prediction. Sending something relatively &quot;big&quot; (by nanotechnological standards) like a chromosome as far back in time as a millisecond would take <a href="http://www.wolframalpha.com/input/?i=%282.1e11+dalton%29+*+%281+millisecond%29^3">orders of magnitude less</a> than a femtoxyank.</li>
</ol>

							</div>

								
					
